orted by other countries to include Great Britain, which released a statement to the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) stating, “not everyone involved (in crypto currency) is shady or involved in criminal activity—principally those outside the United States”. This international rift in fiscal policies are mirrored by US agencies, as legitimacy for crypto currency is gaining traction from the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) and other US government organizations; facilitating the ability of legitimate businesses to accept crypto currency for payment of goods and services. The intent of this research is to demonstrate the transition from government currencies to crypto currencies for purchase and redistribution of EaaS and MaaS activities, creating greater competition and reducing prices through an anonymous transaction process. The authors will provide an explanation of crypto currency, how it is produced, currency distribution, and the ability to conduct anonymous transactions across borders and legal jurisdictions. The authors will present a case study which creates and exchanges crypto currency with minimal risk of detection while engaging in MaaS and EaaS transactions. © 2018 Academic Conferences and Publishing International Limited. All Rights Reserved.},
